portant insights into the role of images in making the practices of the desert saints both compelling and accessible to fourteenth-century city dwellers, who were just beginning to cultivate the habit of private devotion on a wide scale.By focusing on the most extensively illuminated manuscript of the Vitae patrum to emerge during the trecento, this book sheds new light on the ways in which images communicated and reinforced modes of piety. It will be of interest to art historians, religious historians, and students focusing on this period in Italian history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDesert FathersxBiography. 0aIllumination of books and manuscripts, MedievalzItalyzNaples (Kingdom). 0aIllumination of books and manuscripts, Medieval. 7aART / History / Renaissance.2bisacsh  aLives of the Desert Fathers and Mothers.  aMS. M. 626.  aNaples.  aVitae patrum.  aanchoritism.  aeremitic ideal.  alate medieval Italy.  amanuscript illustrations.  aprivate devotion.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079776340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271098043?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271098043423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271098043/original  a978-3-11-079776-3  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles